1.1 Introduction

  • Classes of Computing Applications :
    • Desktop computers
    • Servers :
      • carrying large workloads
      • provide for greater expandability of both computing and input/output
      • place greater emphasis on dependability
      • supercomputer
      • datacenter
    • Embedded computers
  • Program Performance :

1.2 Below Your Program

  • System Software (OS) :
    • handling basic input and output operations
    • allocating storage and memory
    • providing for protected sharing of the computer among multiple applications using it simultaneously
    • Linux, MacOS and Windows
  • Compilers : translations of a program written in a high-level language into instructions that the hardware can execute
  • Assembler : translate a symbolic version of an instruction into a binary version

1.3 Under the Covers

  • Classic components of a computer :
    • input
    • output
    • memory
    • processor :
      • datapath
      • control

Anatomy of a Mouse :
- miniature optical processor
- LED to provide lighting
- black-white camera

  • Glass :
    • Active matrix display : a liquid crystal display using a transistor to control the transmission of light at each individual pixel
    • Bit map : the image is composed of a matrix of picture elements/pixels which is represented as a matrix of bits
      • 8 bits for each color of RGB
      • 24 bits per pixel
    • Raster refresh buffer (frame buffer)
  • Open the box :
    • Motherboard : a plastic board containing packages of integrated circuits or chips
    • Integrated circuits (chip)
    • Memory :
      • dynamic random access memory : the memory access takes basically the same amount of time no matter what portion of the memory is read
      • dual inline memory module (DIMM) : a small board that contains DRAM chips on both sides
    • CPU :
      • datapath : the component of the processor that performs arithmetic operations
      • control : the component of the processor that commands the data path, memory, I/O device according to the instructions
      • cache memory SRAM (static random access memory): small, fast memory that acts as a buffer for the DRAM memory
    • Instruction set architecture : an abstract interface between that hardware and the lowest-level software that encompass all the inform action necessary to write a machine language program
    • Application binary interface (ABI) : combination of the basic instruction set and the operating system interface, standard for binary portability across computers
  • Communicating with other computers :
    • LAN
    • WAN
    • Wireless
  • Processors and memory :

1.4 Performance

  • Execution time (response time) : total time required for the computer to complete a task
    • disk access
    • memory access
    • I/O activities
    • OS overhead
    • CPU execution time
  • Throughput (bandwidth) : number of task completed per unit of time
  • CPU execution time : actual time the CPU spends computing for a specific task
  • User CPU time : the CPU time spent int a program itself
  • System CPU time : the CPU time spent in the OS performing tasks on behalf of the program

1.5 The Power Wall

  • clock rate and power is correlated

For CMOS (complementary metal oxide semiconductors) :

  • Frequency switched is a function of the clock rate
  • Further lowering of the voltage appears to make the transistors too leaky (cannot be completely shut off)
  • 40% of the power consumption is due to leakage
